                "sender": "w-nws.webmaster@noaa.gov",
                "senderName": "NWS Wilmington OH",
                "headline": "Special Weather Statement issued February 22 at 11:02AM EST by NWS Wilmington OH",
                "description": "Snow showers will continue this afternoon into the evening hours.\nSlick spots may develop on roads tonight as temperatures drop and\nnorthwest winds gust from 20 to 30 mph. Coverage of snow showers\nis expected to decrease overnight before ending Monday morning.\nMost the area will see an accumulation of one-half inch to 2\ninches. Visibility will be restricted at times in the heavier\nshowers.\n\nRoadways may become slick. If traveling, be alert, slow down and\nallow extra time to reach your destination.",

                "event": "Heavy Freezing Spray Warning",
                "sender": "w-nws.webmaster@noaa.gov",
                "senderName": "NWS Duluth MN",
                "headline": "Heavy Freezing Spray Warning issued February 22 at 9:53AM CST until February 23 at 6:00AM CST by NWS Duluth MN",
                "description": "* WHAT...For the Heavy Freezing Spray Warning, heavy freezing\nspray at a rate of 2 cm per hour or greater may rapidly\naccumulate on vessels. For the Small Craft Advisory, north\nwinds 10 to 20 kt with gusts up to 25 kt and waves 3 to 6 ft.\n\n* WHERE...Outer Apostle Islands Beyond 5 NM from Mainland.\n\n* WHEN...Until 6 AM CST Monday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Operating a vessel in heavy freezing spray is\nhazardous. Freezing spray may render mechanical and electronic\ncomponents inoperative. Rapid ice accretion on decks and\nsuperstructures may result in a catastrophic loss of\nstability. Conditions will be hazardous to small craft.",
                "instruction": "Mariners should prepare for dangerous accumulation of ice on\ntheir vessel. If possible, remain in port, avoid the warning area\nor conduct mitigation.\n\nAnyone operating a smaller vessel should avoid navigating in\nhazardous conditions.",
                "response": "Avoid",
                "parameters": {
                    "AWIPSidentifier": [
                        "MWWDLH"
                    ],
                    "WMOidentifier": [
                        "WHUS73 KDLH 221553"
                    ],

                "headline": "Flood Warning issued February 22 at 9:10AM CST until February 27 at 6:00AM CST by NWS Little Rock AR",
                "description": "...The Flood Warning continues for the following rivers in\nArkansas...\n\nCache River Near Patterson affecting Woodruff and Jackson\nCounties.\n\nFor the Cache River...including Patterson...Minor flooding is\nforecast.\n\n* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.\n\n* WHERE...Cache River near Patterson.\n\n* WHEN...Until further notice.\n\n* IMPACTS...At 10.0 feet, Pastureland and cropland not protected by\nlevees in Jackson and Woodruff counties affected. Water is over\nportions of State Highway 37 and deep along the shoulders of State\nHighway 18 near Grubbs. Water over portions of Woodruff County\nRoad 775 north of State Highway 260.\n\n* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...\n- At 8:15 AM CST Sunday the stage was 9.9 feet.\n- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage\nearly Thursday morning and continue falling to 8.6 feet\nFriday morning.\n- Flood stage is 9.0 feet.\n- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood",
                "instruction": "Motorists should not attempt to drive around barricades or drive\ncars through flooded areas.\n\nRiver forecasts are based on current conditions and rainfall\nforecasted to occur over the next 24 hours.                 "description": "Low pressure near Cape Hatteras, North Carolina, will strengthen\ninto a major winter storm as in moves north along the East Coast.\n\n* WHAT...Snow. Total snow accumulations up to 3 inches. Winds\ngusting as high as 45 mph.\n\n* WHERE...In Virginia, Bland, Giles, and Bath Counties.                 "description": "SABPIH\n\nThe following message is transmitted at the request of the\nForest Service Utah Avalanche Center.\n\nThe Forest Service Utah Avalanche Center has issued a SPECIAL\nAVALANCHE BULLETIN for the following areas:\n\n* WHAT...Dangerous avalanche conditions are possible across the\nBear River Range and surrounding mountains across northern Utah\nthis weekend. This week's heavy snowfall and strong winds\noverloaded preexisting weak layers, creating HIGH avalanche\ndanger. With improving weather moving in for the weekend,\navalanche accidents are likely in the backcountry. There have\nalready been two avalanche fatalities this week, as well as\nseveral close calls and numerous backcountry avalanches\nreported.\n\n* WHERE...Bear River Range and surrounding mountains across northern\nUtah.\n\n* WHEN...6 AM MST Monday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Dangerous avalanche conditions exist in the mountains\nand will persist through the weekend.",
                "instruction": "Natural avalanches are possible, and people are likely to trigger\navalanches on slopes steeper than 30 degrees. Dangerous and deadly\navalanches can be triggered remotely from a distance or from\nbelow.                 "senderName": "NWS Mount Holly NJ",
                "headline": "Winter Storm Warning issued February 22 at 6:00AM EST until February 23 at 6:00PM EST by NWS Mount Holly NJ",
                "description": "...POTENTIALLY HISTORIC WINTER STORM WILL IMPACT THE REGION THROUGH\nMONDAY...\n\n.A major winter storm is expected to develop today, impacting the\nregion with very heavy, crippling snowfall and areas of blizzard\nconditions. Precipitation will develop today, changing to all snow\nthis afternoon and evening. The most severe conditions and heaviest\nsnowfall will occur tonight, with snow gradually tapering off during\nthe daytime Monday. Record breaking snowfall totals are possible.\n\n* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations between 16\nand 22 inches. Winds gusting as high as 40 mph.\n\n* WHERE...Eastern Chester, Western Chester, and Western Montgomery\nCounties.\n\n* WHEN...Until 6 PM EST Monday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Areas of\nblowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The hazardous\nconditions will impact the Monday morning and evening commutes.\nGusty winds could bring down tree branches and result in isolated\npower outages.\n\n* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snowfall rates could exceed 2 inches per\nhour. Locally higher snowfall amounts possible. Blowing and\ndrifting of snow, and whiteout conditions possible.",
                "instruction": "If you must travel, keep an extra flashlight, food, and water in\nyour vehicle in case of an emergency. The latest road conditions for\nthe state you are calling from can be obtained by calling 5 1 1.",

                "instruction": "If you must travel, keep an extra flashlight, food, and water in\nyour vehicle in case of an emergency.                 "headline": "Winter Storm Warning issued February 22 at 5:07AM EST until February 23 at 7:00PM EST by NWS Albany NY",
                "description": "* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations between 5 and\n12 inches with locally higher amounts into the Helderbergs and\nSchoharie County.                 "description": "* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations between 10\nand 20 inches with locally higher amounts possible in the eastern\nCatskills. Winds gusting as high as 45 mph will lead to widespread\nblowing snow and near blizzard conditions at times.\n\n* WHERE...Litchfield County in northwestern Connecticut, the\nBerkshires in western Massachusetts, and Ulster, Greene, Columbia\nand Dutchess Counties in eastern New York.\n\n* WHEN...From 1 PM this afternoon to 7 PM EST Monday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Travel could be difficult to impossible. The hazardous\nconditions will impact the Monday morning and evening commutes.\nVisibilities may drop below 1/4 mile due to falling and blowing\nsnow.                 "senderName": "NWS Tiyan GU",
                "headline": "Small Craft Advisory issued February 22 at 4:48PM ChST until February 24 at 5:00PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU",
                "description": "* WHAT...Northeast winds 15 to 25 kt with gusts up to 30 kt and\nseas 8 to 11 feet expected.\n\n* WHERE...Tinian and Saipan Coastal Waters.\n\n* WHEN...Until 5 PM ChST Tuesday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Conditions will be hazardous to small craft.\n\n* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Winds and seas will begin to rapidly\nincrease late tonight, from north to south across the Marianas\nas a shear line shifts southward through the area. Combined\nseas will build to near 11 feet around Monday morning as\nsustained winds increase to around 22 knots. These strong winds\nwill continue to propagate south across Rota and Guam waters\nstarting around Monday evening, and the Small Craft Advisory\nwill likely be expanded to include these coastal zones. After a\nbrief lull in hazardous conditions Tuesday, seas and winds will\nrapidly increase Tuesday night as a significant trade-wind surge\nbuilds behind the shear line, reinforcing the north-northeast\nswell and wind waves. Combined seas may begin to reach 15 feet\nby Wednesday morning as winds become fresh to strong, with\nfrequent near-gale to gale-force gusts possible. Seas and winds\nwill begin to relax by the end of the week, after a peak in\nhazardous conditions around Wednesday. However, as seas remain\nelevated, a Small Craft Advisory may need to be maintained into\nthe weekend.",

Then, a significant trade swell is\nexpected to move through the Marianas, reinforced by a strong\ntrade-wind surge behind the shear line. Surf will increase\nfurther and could become dangerous at times along north and east\nfacing reefs, especially around Tuesday night and Wednesday.",

                "description": "...RED FLAG WARNING IN EFFECT FOR JIM HOGG, STARR, BROOKS, HIDALGO\nAND INLAND PORTIONS OF CAMERON, WILLACY AND KENEDY COUNTIES ON\nSUNDAY...\n\nThe National Weather Service in Brownsville has issued a Red Flag\nWarning for gusty winds and low relative humidity, which is in\neffect from 9 AM to 6 PM CST Sunday.                 "headline": "Hydrologic Outlook issued February 21 at 2:29PM PST by NWS Medford OR",
                "description": "ESFMFR\n\nA moderate atmospheric river will likely bring periods of moderate\nto heavy rainfall later this weekend into early next week. The first\nfrontal system is forecast to arrive late Saturday night into Sunday\nwith multiple waves of precipitation continuing Sunday night through\nMonday, then a Pineapple Express Monday night into Tuesday.\nPreliminary estimates are showing widespread\namounts of 4 to 6 inches along the coast with locally 8 inches in\nthe favored coast ranges of Curry County. Amounts of 3 to 5 inches\nare possible in the Mount Shasta region and also other favored areas\nof western Siskiyou County.\n\nSmall streams and creeks are likely to rise rapidly during this\nevent with nuisance flooding and ponding of water on roadways during\nperiods of heavy rain. Significant rises on main stem rivers and\nflashier creeks are also expected. Given that rivers are still\nrunning fairly low for this time of year, river flooding potential\nis a bit lower than usual, but there is at least a low probability\nof some flooding, especially in the Coquille Basin.\n\nThe warm rain expected MOnday night into Tuesday, with snow levels\nwell above 7000 feet, will cause concern for heavy rain to combine\nwith snowmelt, which would lead to even higher rises.\n\nWhile the exact scenario for the heavy rainfall and potential\nflooding remains uncertain, we will continue to monitor the\nforecasts and update accordingly. Flood Watches may be issued by the\nNational Weather Service if this situation worsens.",

                "headline": "Coastal Flood Warning issued February 21 at 2:44PM EST until February 23 at 5:00AM EST by NWS Upton NY",
                "description": "* WHAT...1 1/2 to 2 1/2 ft of inundation above ground level likely\nin vulnerable areas near the waterfront and shoreline.\n\n* WHERE...Bronx, Northwest Suffolk, Northern Queens and Northern\nNassau Counties.\n\n* WHEN...From midnight Sunday night to 5 AM EST Monday.\n\n* COASTAL FLOOD IMPACTS...Widespread moderate flooding of\nvulnerable areas near the waterfront and shoreline likely. 1\n1/2 to 2 1/2 ft of inundation above ground level possible in low\nlying, vulnerable areas. This would result in numerous road\nclosures and cause widespread flooding of low lying property\nincluding parking lots, parks, lawns and homes/businesses with\nbasements near the waterfront. Vehicles parked in vulnerable\nareas near the waterfront will likely become flooded. Flooding\nwill also extend inland from the waterfront along tidal rivers\nand bays. Ice cover in the bays and harbors could exacerbate\nflooding and cause damage to northeast to east facing shoreline\nstructure.\n\n* SHORELINE IMPACTS...Breaking surf of 3 to 5 ft along north and\nnortheast facing shorelines will cause beach flooding and dune\nerosion during the time of high tide. This may also exacerbate\nsplashover flooding of shorelines roads and properties behind\nprotective dunes, structures and seawalls. Minor damage to\nshoreline structures possible.\n\n* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...This water level forecast will be highly\ndependent on timing of windshift from northeast to north storm\nforce winds with respect to the time of high tide, and will be\nrefined over the next 24 hours.                 "event": "Avalanche Advisory",
                "sender": "w-nws.webmaster@noaa.gov",
                "senderName": "NWS Salt Lake City UT",
                "headline": "Avalanche Advisory issued February 20 at 5:52AM MST by NWS Salt Lake City UT",
                "description": "SABSLC\n\n* WHAT...The Utah Avalanche Center is warning of dangerous\navalanche conditions across all Utah mountains this weekend.\nThis week's heavy snowfall and strong winds overloaded\npreexisting weak layers, creating a HIGH avalanche danger across\nthe entire state. With improving weather moving in for the\nweekend, avalanche accidents are likely in the backcountry.\nThere have already been two tragic avalanche fatalities this\nweek, as well as several close calls and numerous backcountry\navalanches reported.\n\n* WHERE...The mountains of Utah and southeast Idaho.\n\n* WHEN...6 AM MST Friday, February 20th 2006 until Monday,\nFebruary 23rd 2006 at 6 AM MST.\n\n* IMPACTS...Dangerous avalanche conditions exist in the\nbackcountry and will persist through the weekend. Natural\navalanches are possible, and people are likely to trigger\navalanches on slopes steeper than 30 degrees. Dangerous and\ndeadly avalanches can be triggered remotely (from a distance or\nfrom below). People leaving ski area boundaries are entering the\nbackcountry where the same dangerous avalanche conditions exist.",
                "instruction": "Backcountry travelers should consult www.utahavalanchecenter.org\nor call 1-888-999-4019 for more detailed information.\n\nThis Bulletin does not apply to ski areas or highways where\navalanche hazard reduction measures are performed.",
                "response": "Monitor",
                "parameters": {
                    "AWIPSidentifier": [
                        "SABSLC"
                    ],
                    "WMOidentifier": [

                "headline": "Avalanche Advisory issued February 19 at 5:31PM MST by NWS Denver CO",
                "description": "SABCO\n\nTHE FOLLOWING MESSAGE IS TRANSMITTED AT THE REQUEST OF THE\nCOLORADO AVALANCHE INFORMATION CENTER.\n\nA SPECIAL AVALANCHE ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM THURSDAY EVENING\nTHROUGH SUNDAY\n\n\n*WHATit is very easy for people to trigger large and deadly\navalanches through the weekend.\n\n\n*WHEREthe Elkheads, Park Range, Flat Tops, Front Range, Gore Range,\n10-Mile Range, Grand Mesa, Sawatch, West Elk, Elk Mountains, San\nJuan Mountains.\n\n\n*WHENDangerous avalanche conditions exist through Sunday.\n\n\n*IMPACTSLarge and dangerous avalanches will be easy to trigger.\n\n\n*PRECAUTION/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS Travel in backcountry avalanche\nterrain  requires careful planning and cautious route-finding to\nstay safe. Many slopes that were safe earlier this winter are now\ndangerous. Avoid travel on and under slopes with a slope angle\nsteeper than about 30 degrees. You can find more detailed\ninformation at colorado.gov/avalanche\n\n\nPritchett",
